parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Carbon Monoxide (CO) Leaks into Vehicle Cabin
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Carbon monoxide leaks into the vehicle cabin can cause serious health issues, including headaches, dizziness, nausea, and even death, due to the toxic nature of CO.
symptoms: Unusual exhaust smell inside the cabin
especially when the vehicle is idling or in remote start mode
shortness of breath
chest pain
lethargy
and near-fainting while driving.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the EPS system can cause uncommanded steering, delayed response to steering inputs, and difficulty in correcting the vehicle's direction, which can lead to loss of control and accidents.
symptoms: Uncommanded steering
delayed response to steering inputs
mismatch between steering wheel angle and wheel direction
sudden return to commanded input
slow deviation to left or right while driving in a straight line
abrupt return to center line when corrected
steering wheel logo appears off-center
difficulty in turning the wheel in any direction
loss of power steering assistance.

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Passenger Side Front Brake Hose Failure
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the passenger side front brake hose can cause a loss of brake fluid, leading to a spongy brake pedal, reduced braking performance, and increased stopping distances, which can lead to accidents or injuries.
symptoms: Spongy brake pedal
brake fluid low warning light illumination
brake fluid leaking from the passenger side front brake hose
split or bubble at the body side connection where the metal is crimped to the rubber.

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Cracked Exhaust Manifold Causing Carbon Monoxide Infiltration
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The cracked exhaust manifold allows carbon monoxide to leak into the cabin, posing a significant risk to the health and safety of occupants, especially when the vehicle is stationary with the engine idling.
symptoms: Exhaust fumes entering the cabin through the heater/AC vents
strong smell of exhaust fumes at the passenger side of the hood
carbon monoxide readings detected by a CO detector placed in front of the AC vent
readings drop to 0 ppm when the vehicle is moving.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the rear exhaust manifold can cause carbon monoxide to leak into the cabin, posing a significant risk to the health and safety of occupants, especially when the vehicle is stationary with the engine idling.
symptoms: High carbon monoxide readings detected by a CO detector placed around the rear exhaust manifold
especially around the center exhaust port
strong smell of exhaust fumes at the passenger side of the hood.
